---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { getPost } from '../../data/posts';
import { engageHref, products, withBase } from '../../site.config';

const post = getPost('soc2-gke-series-b')!;
const siteOrigin = Astro.site?.origin ?? 'https://sollabs.tech';
const structuredData = [
  {
    '@type': 'BlogPosting',
    headline: post.title,
    datePublished: post.date,
    description: post.description,
    author: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'Sol Labs' },
    publisher: { '@id': `${siteOrigin}/#organization` },
  },
];
---

<Layout
  title={`${post.title} · Sol Labs`}
  description={post.description}
  current="blog"
  ogType="article"
  publishedTime={post.date}
  structuredData={structuredData}
>
  <article class="page-wrap">
    <div class="prose">
      <p class="meta">{post.date} · {post.icp}</p>
      <h1>{post.title}</h1>
      <p>
        Series B teams on Google Cloud often hear two incomplete stories. The first: use a secure
        multi-project landing zone and inherit Google’s platform controls. The second: buy GRC SaaS,
        write policies, and collect screenshots. Both matter. Neither finishes the job when your
        production surface is GKE.
      </p>

      <h2>What landing zones actually buy you</h2>
      <p>
        Org folders, baseline IAM, and logging foundations reduce blank-page risk. Google’s own SOC 2
        reports cover the platform layer. Auditors still ask what <em>you</em> do with identities,
        change management, network boundaries, and workload privileges on the clusters you run.
        Practitioner guidance puts inherited controls in the minority of the control set — useful,
        not sufficient (
        <a href="https://linfordco.com/blog/google-cloud-gcp-soc-2/">Linford on GCP SOC 2</a>).
      </p>

      <h2>The GKE gap</h2>
      <p>Starter Terraform rarely ships the full production control plane:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Private clusters and restricted control-plane access</li>
        <li>Workload Identity Federation instead of long-lived service account keys</li>
        <li>GitOps (Argo CD) with SSO, least-privilege RBAC, and production sync gates</li>
        <li>Git history and sync events retained as change evidence</li>
        <li>Admission controls, namespace isolation, and audit log retention for the observation window</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        That gap is where enterprise deals stall: the GRC tool is green, the cluster still cannot
        explain who shipped what, when, and under which approval.
      </p>

      <h2>GRC tools are complementary</h2>
      <p>
        Vanta, Drata, and peers are good at evidence collection and policy workflow. They do not
        replace private GKE design or GitOps discipline. Positioning Sol Labs against them as a
        “competitor” is a category error — the buyer needs both the platform wiring and the evidence
        pipeline.
      </p>

      <h2>What a scoped sprint should leave behind</h2>
      <p>
        A useful engagement does not “get you certified.” It leaves Terraform, GitOps, and a control
        map your team can operate — so SOC 2 observation is review of existing evidence, not a
        scramble. See the outcome page and
        <a href={products.kanto.href}>Kanto</a> for the product receipt behind this lane.
      </p>

      <p>
        <a class="btn btn--primary" href={engageHref}>Book a call</a>
        {' '}
        <a class="btn btn--secondary" href={withBase('/outcomes/soc2-gke/')}>SOC 2 / GKE outcome</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>
